<font color="#FF0000">HERE WE GO AGAIN!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb  1  1:10:34 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Cook and MTF,<br><br>
I have tried, over this last year, not to take sides.  My wish is to convey that many things we take for granted in this society can be seen by some in a much different light.  Cook, I agree with much of what you say.  What I'm also trying to do, however, is to reinforce how others who are not from your particular background might see things.  In that way, I'm trying to hold up a mirror to show how your post might be perceived by others.  And yes, politicians must be very careful about what they say and do.  <br><br>
I have said time and again that I will make my own evaluation of what is said, and freely express it.  In doing so, I sometimes agree and sometimes do not.  That does not mean that I do not respect those, including you, Cookie, who post here.  There is only one, so far, who has lost my respect who has posted here.  Actually, that person lost respect of us first.  <br><br>
The need for being very careful of what we do and say holds for Clinton too.  If indeed he did what he's accused of, he has some real problems.  If he lied, he shouldn't remain where he is.  But I don't have any friends or relatives who are grieving the loss of a loved one over it!  I don't have to lecture you about sins; you already know much more than I.  But who is hurting?  Johnson sent our fighters out to bomb non-effective targets to &quot;give the North Vietnamese a message.&quot;  The message we got in return is, &quot;We've got some of your pilots.&quot;  People suffered from these decisions, and suffered greatly.  Some are still suffering, long after LBJ is dead.  Clinton's behavior, if it is true--sordid, yes; embarrassing, yes; a national tragedy, not yet, at least.<br><br>
Now, God forbid, we're going to send Sadam a message.  More fighters may take off, and we may loose some.  I hope there is a very good reason to put these people in harm's way.  If it's just to send a message that Sadam needs to abide by the UN inspector's wishes, and it's ineffective in doing so or worse, precipitates a greater conflict, then even Clinton will not have learned the lessons of Vietnam!  <br><br>
MTF, I hear your sorrow about the current situation.  Let us hope, and pray, that dialog resumes, that we will not again face the situations we have been discussing in this last year.  <br><br>
Iraq may loose a lot, but unless it is Sadam who personally looses, I don't see military action doing any good.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


